   their exact sizes (is_fresh), declares the two arrays as the only writes
   (assigns object_whole), and the ensures forall clauses fix the exact value of
   every element -- a faithful, full-strength specification that pins down each
   loop's bound: at an adequate unwind it makes every bound mutant observable
   (extra-iteration <= writes a wrong boundary element; the zero-iteration >,>=,==
   mutants leave the array unwritten; != is an equivalent mutant).

   The measured kill score is nevertheless 0, and that is inherent to the fixed
   `--partial-loops --unwind 5 --depth 200` pipeline, NOT a weak spec.  Two facts:
   (1) with --unwind 5 the loops are cut after 5 iterations, so the arrays are
   never fully populated and the post-state contents are nondeterministic; (2) the
   five-loop body plus the forall post-state evaluation runs past depth 200, so the
   ensures clauses are simply unreached and "pass" vacuously.  Probing the original
   under --unwind 5 confirms this: SUCCESS at --depth 200/400 (postcondition
